adjectives.description: superfine (comparative more superfine, superlative most superfine)

entries.meaning: Extremely subtle or refined; extremely sensitive to slight impressions or perceptions. [from 16th c.]
examples: The bulk of Mankind have not leisure for Learning and Logick, and superfine distinctions of the Schools.

entries.meaning: Extremely refined or sophisticated; very elegant. [from 16th c.]
examples: This place, with regard to superfine visitors, fills slowly and the season is expected not only to be late, but thin, of company, from the many families that are rambling abroad.

entries.meaning: Having an especially fine size or texture; made of very small particles or threads. [from 17th c.]
examples: Some recipes call for superfine sugar because it dissolves easier.

entries.meaning: Of a very high or pure grade or quality. [from 17th c.]
